 =Hoshi no Umi E\n|music8  =Various\n|length8 =0:49\n|title9  =Kowaremono - Fragile\n|music9  =[[Kuwashima Houko (musician)|Kuwashima Houko]]\n|length9 =2:18\n|title10  =Pilgrimage No.3\n|music10  =[[Katsuhisa Hattori (musician)|Katsuhisa Hattori]]\n|length10 =5:02\n|title11  =Epilogue\n|music11  =Various\n|length11 =1:40\n}}\n{{-}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{ann|anime|413}}\n* {{IMDb title|0353039}}\n* {{tv.com show|argento-soma|Argento Soma}}\n\n{{Sunrise}}\n\n[[Category:2000 anime television series]]\n[[Category:2002 anime OVAs]]\n[[Category:Adventure anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Anime with original screenplays]]\n[[Category:Bandai Entertainment anime titles]]\n[[Category:Mecha anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Odex]]\n[[Category:Sentai Filmworks]]\n[[Category:Sunrise (company)]]\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argento_Soma"}
{"title_page": "Charles Mason Hovey", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=March 2013}}\n\n[[File:Charles Mason Hovey00.jpg|thumb|right]]\n[[File:Charles Mason Hovey01.jpg|thumb|<center>Plate by [[William Sharp (lithographer)|William Sharp]]</center>]]\n'''Charles Mason Hovey''' (October 26, 1810, [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] - 1887) was an American nurseryman, seed merchant, journalist and author of horticultural books best known for his two-volume large [[quarto]], ''The Fruits of America''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/66669#page/17/mode/1up |title=''The Fruits of America''|publisher=Biodiversitylibrary.org|accessdate=2012-08-01}}</ref>  published between 1848 and 1856 and containing some 100 [[chromolithographs]] by [[William Sharp (lithographer)|William Sharp]], the British-born lithographer and artist, with an extremely rare third volume which was partly published.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.donaldheald.com/books/Botany/books_text_01.php?cat=Botany&pg=8 |title=Donald Heald Original Antique Books Prints and Maps - Books |publisher=Donaldheald.com |accessdate=2012-07-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419032013/http://www.donaldheald.com/books/Botany/books_text_01.php?cat=Botany |archivedate=2012-04-19 }}</ref>\n\nHovey was an honorary member of the Royal Societies of London and of Edinburgh.\n\n==Biography==\nCharles was the sixth of seven children born to Sarah Stone Hovey and Phineas Brown Hovey, who ran a grocery store at the comer of Main and Brookline Streets, and dealt in the sale and rental of property in Cambridge. In 1832 Hovey and his brother Phineas started ''Hovey & Co.'', a seed store and nursery in Cambridge, the nursery eventually growing to 40 acres in extent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/How-to-Trademark-a-Fruit.html# |title=Smithsonian.com |publisher=Smithsonianmag.com |date=2012-03-16 |accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref> Hovey set out to publish a magazine that would appeal to gardeners and showcase the various American fruits of interest. He became the editor of the ''Magazine of Horticulture'' published between 1835 and 1868, founded as ''The American Gardener's Magazine'' with a name change in 1837. It enjoyed a longer life than any other American horticultural journal and was modelled on [[John Claudius Loudon]]'s ''Gardener's Magazine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcs.ohio-state.edu/hort/history/158.html |title='&#39;History of Horticulture'&#39; |publisher=Hcs.ohio-state.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref>\n\nHovey collected cultivars of pear, apple, plum and grape, also cultivating florist and ornamental plants, with a particular fondness for ''[[Camellia]]'' and ''[[Chrysanthemum]]''. He exhibited regularly with the [[Massachusetts Horticultural Society]] and was its president for four years. He was responsible for producing the ''Hovey Strawberry'' in 1836, regarded as the foundation of the [[New England]] strawberry industry, and grown on a large scale until about 1890. Hovey wrote a seminal article \"''Some Remarks upon the Production of new varieties of Strawberries from Seeds''\" that was published July 1837 in his ''Magazine of Horticulture'', and in which he gave detailed instructions for producing hybrids.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nal.usda.gov/pgdic/Strawberry/book/boktwel.htm |title=12 Notable Early Strawberry Breeders of America |publisher=Nal.usda.gov |accessdate=2012-07-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702173338/http://www.nal.usda.gov/pgdic/Strawberry/book/boktwel.htm |archive-date=2012-07-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHovey was a great champion of open spaces and wrote in the ''Magazine of Horticulture'': \"We need not enlarge upon the importance of public parks, certainly, if they were more numerous they would prevent the useless expenditure of money for lunatic hospitals. What the busy people of the city need is pure air, the sight of green trees, the smell of the fresh turf \u2013 extensive grounds, where they can enjoy the pleasures of the country, and find relief from the busy hours engaged in the turmoil of trade.\" Philadelphia nurseryman, botanist and author, [[Thomas Meehan (botanist)|Thomas Meehan]], credited Hovey with the growth of American horticulture.\n\nToday, the only visible evidence of Hovey's nursery are the names given to the short streets within the subdivisions created on parts of his land in the 1890s: Hovey, Myrtle, Magnolia and Camellia Avenues.  These now compose a quiet little neighborhood of one, two and three-family homes, about a mile east of Harvard Yard, between Kirkland and Cambridge Streets, near the Cambridge/Somerville city line.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Charles Mason Hovey}}\n* [https://www.lindahall.org/charles-hovey/ Scientist of the Day-Charles Hovey] at [[Linda Hall Library]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hovey, Charles Mason}}\n[[Category:American horticulturists]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:1810 births]]\n[[Category:1887 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=March 2013}}\n\n[[File:Charles Mason Hovey00.jpg|thumb|right]]\n[[File:Charles Mason Hovey01.jpg|thumb|<center>Plate by [[William Sharp (lithographer)|William Sharp]]</center>]]\n'''Charles Mason Hovey''' (October 26, 1810, [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] - 1887) was an American nurseryman, seed merchant, journalist and author of horticultural books best known for his two-volume large [[quarto]], ''The Fruits of America''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/66669#page/17/mode/1up |title=''The Fruits of America''|publisher=Biodiversitylibrary.org|accessdate=2012-08-01}}</ref>  published between 1848 and 1856 and containing some 100 [[chromolithographs]] by [[William Sharp (lithographer)|William Sharp]], the British-born lithographer and artist, with an extremely rare third volume which was partly published.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.donaldheald.com/books/Botany/books_text_01.php?cat=Botany&pg=8 |title=Donald Heald Original Antique Books Prints and Maps - Books |publisher=Donaldheald.com |accessdate=2012-07-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419032013/http://www.donaldheald.com/books/Botany/books_text_01.php?cat=Botany |archivedate=2012-04-19 }}</ref>\n\nHovey was an honorary member of the Royal Societies of London and of Edinburgh.\n\n==Biography==\nCharles was the sixth of seven children born to Sarah Stone Hovey and Phineas Brown Hovey, who ran a grocery store at the comer of Main and Brookline Streets, and dealt in the sale and rental of property in Cambridge. In 1832 Hovey and his brother Phineas started ''Hovey & Co.'', a seed store and nursery in Cambridge, the nursery eventually growing to 40 acres in extent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/How-to-Trademark-a-Fruit.html# |title=Smithsonian.com |publisher=Smithsonianmag.com |date=2012-03-16 |accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref> Hovey set out to publish a magazine that would appeal to gardeners and showcase the various American fruits of interest. He became the editor of the ''Magazine of Horticulture'' published between 1835 and 1868, founded as ''The American Gardener's Magazine'' with a name change in 1837. It enjoyed a longer life than any other American horticultural journal and was modelled on [[John Claudius Loudon]]'s ''Gardener's Magazine''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcs.ohio-state.edu/hort/history/158.html |title='&#39;History of Horticulture'&#39; |publisher=Hcs.ohio-state.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref>\n\nHovey collected cultivars of pear, apple, plum and grape, also cultivating florist and ornamental plants, with a particular fondness for ''[[Camellia]]'' and ''[[Chrysanthemum]]''. He exhibited regularly with the [[Massachusetts Horticultural Society]] and was its president for four years. He was responsible for producing the ''Hovey Strawberry'' in 1836, regarded as the foundation of the [[New England]] strawberry industry, and grown on a large scale until about 1890. Hovey wrote a seminal article \"''Some Remarks upon the Production of new varieties of Strawberries from Seeds''\" that was published July 1837 in his ''Magazine of Horticulture'', and in which he gave detailed instructions for producing hybrids.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nal.usda.gov/pgdic/Strawberry/book/boktwel.htm |title=12 Notable Early Strawberry Breeders of America |publisher=Nal.usda.gov |accessdate=2012-07-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702173338/http://www.nal.usda.gov/pgdic/Strawberry/book/boktwel.htm |archive-date=2012-07-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHovey was a great champion of open spaces and wrote in the ''Magazine of Horticulture'': \"We need not enlarge upon the importance of public parks, certainly, if they were more numerous they would prevent the useless expenditure of money for lunatic hospitals. What the busy people of the city need is pure air, the sight of green trees, the smell of the fresh turf \u2013 extensive grounds, where they can enjoy the pleasures of the country, and find relief from the busy hours engaged in the turmoil of trade.\" Philadelphia nurseryman, botanist and author, [[Thomas Meehan (botanist)|Thomas Meehan]], credited Hovey with the growth of American horticulture.\n\nToday, the only visible evidence of Hovey's nursery are the names given to the short streets within the subdivisions created on parts of his land in the 1890s: Hovey, Myrtle, Magnolia and Camellia Avenues.  These now compose a quiet little neighborhood of one, two and three-family homes, about a mile east of Harvard Yard, between Kirkland and Cambridge Streets, near the Cambridge/Somerville city line.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Charles Mason Hovey}}\n* [https://www.lindahall.org/charles-hovey/ Scientist of the Day-Charles Hovey] at [[Linda Hall Library]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hovey, Charles Mason}}\n[[Category:American horticulturists]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:1810 births]]\n[[Category:1887 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Mason_Hovey"}
{"title_page": "Demographics of Metro Vancouver", "text_new": "[[Greater Vancouver|Metro Vancouver]] is a metropolitan area, with its major urban centre being [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, Canada. The Vancouver [[Census Metropolitan Area]] is roughly coterminous with the [[Metro Vancouver Regional District]], a [[List of regional districts of British Columbia|regional district in British Columbia]]. The regional district includes 23 local authorities. Figures provided here are for the Vancouver Census Metropolitan Area, and not for the City of Vancouver.\n\n==Population growth==\nThe following table shows the development of the number of inhabitants according to [[Census in Canada|census]] data of [[Statistics Canada]]. The former municipalities of Point Grey and South Vancouver are not included in the data prior to 1931.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vpl.ca/branches/LibrarySquare/soc/pdfs/QF_Population_BC_Vancouver.pdf|title=Vancouver Public Library|format=PDF|accessdate=2007-02-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070614201558/http://www.vpl.ca/branches/LibrarySquare/soc/pdfs/QF_Population_BC_Vancouver.pdf|archivedate=2007-06-14}}</ref>  NB Vancouver did not exist as such at the time of the 1881 and 1871 censuses.<!--data exists for Gastown, Hastings/New Brighton and McLeery's Farm/Marpole, but native population should be accounted for - and IS IT in the 1891 and 1901 etc eensuses??-->\n\n[[File:VanPop.jpg|thumb|upright=2.27|right|Population growth<ref>Data taken from: {{cite web|title=British Columbia Regional District and Municipal Census Populations |publisher=BC Stats |url=http://www.bcstats.gov.bc.ca/data/dd/handout/hist_cen.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate= }}; {{cite web|title=British Columbia Municipal and Regional District 1996 Census Results |publisher=BC Stats |url=http://www.bcstats.gov.bc.ca/data/cen96/mun_rd.asp |accessdate= }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }};{{cite web|title=British Columbia Municipal and Regional District 2001 Census Results |publisher=BC Stats |url=http://www.bcstats.gov.bc.ca/data/cen01/mun_rd.asp |accessdate= }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }};{{cite book| last = Davis| first = Chuck| title = The Greater Vancouver Book: An Urban Encyclopedia| publisher = Linkman Press| year = 1997| location = Surrey, BC| isbn = 978-1-896846-00-2| page = 780}}</ref>]]\n\n{{Historical populations\n|title       = Vancouver\n|typw        = Canada\n|align       = centre\n|width       = \n|state       = \n|shading     = \n|percentages = \n|footnote    =\n|1891|13709\n|1901|26133\n|[[Canada 1911 Census|1911]]|100401\n|1921|117217\n|1931|246593\n|1941|275353\n|1951|344833\n|1956|365844\n|1961|384522\n|1966|410375\n|1971|426256\n|1976|410188\n|1981|414281\n|1986|431147\n|1991|471644\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|514008\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|545671\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|578041\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|603502\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|631486\n}}\n{{Historical populations\n|title       = Metro Vancouver\n|type        = Canada\n|align       = centre\n|width       =\n|state       =\n|shading     =\n|percentages =\n|footnote    =\n|1891|21887\n|1901|42926\n|[[Canada 1911 Census|1911]]|164020\n|1921|232597\n|1931|347709\n|1941|393898\n|1951|562462\n|1961|790741\n|1971|1028334\n|1981|1169831\n|1991|1602590\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|1831665\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|1986965\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|2116581\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|2313328\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|2463431\n}}\n\n==Ethnic origin==\nThe demographics of Metro Vancouver reveal a [[Multiculturalism|multi-ethnic]] society. There remains a small population, less than 2%, of [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal peoples]], who according to [[archeology|archeological]] and [[history|historical]] records, have inhabited this region for more than 3,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}}\n\nFrom the time of the region's first non-indigenous settlement in the second half of the 19th century, people from [[Great Britain|Britain]] and [[Ireland]] were the largest group of immigrants and, collectively, remain the largest ethnic grouping in Vancouver to this day. The largest non British or Irish ethnic groups situated in Vancouver include [[Han Chinese|Chinese]], [[Indian people|Indians]] and [[ethnic German|Germans]].\n\nThe metropolitan area has one of the most diverse Chinese-speaking communities with several [[varieties of Chinese]] being represented. Metro Vancouver contains the second-largest [[Chinatown, Vancouver|Chinatown]] in North America (after [[Chinatown, San Francisco|San Francisco's]]), and many multicultural neighbourhoods such as the [[Punjabi Market, Vancouver|Punjabi Market]], [[Greektown, Vancouver|Greektown]], and [[Japantown, Vancouver|Japantown]]. [[Commercial Drive (Vancouver)|Commercial Drive]], the core of the historic [[Little Italy, Vancouver|Little Italy]], which is also the main Portuguese area, has become an alternative-culture focus, though traditional Italian and Portuguese and other establishments and residents remain in the area.  Bilingual street signs can be seen in Chinatown and the Punjabi Market, and commercial signs in a wide array of languages can be seen all over the metropolitan area.\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break|width=40%}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:20px;\"\n|+[[Panethnicity|Pan-ethnic groups]] in Vancouver [[Census metropolitan areas|CMA]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Vancouver [Census metropolitan area], British Columbia and British Columbia [Province]|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMACA&Code1=933&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1}}</ref>\n|-\n!Ethnic origin\n!Population\n!Percent\n|-\n| [[European Canadian|European]] \n| 1,195,185 \n| {{Percentage | 1195185 | 2426235| 1}}\n|-\n| [[East Asia|East Asian]] \n| 557,745\n| {{Percentage | 557745| 2426235| 1}}\n|-\n| [[South Asian Canadians in Greater Vancouver|South Asian]] \n| 291,005 \n| {{Percentage | 291005 | 2426235| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Southeast Asia]]n \n| 168,075\n| {{Percentage | 168075| 2426235| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] \n| 74,700 \n| {{Percentage | 74700 | 2426235| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Middle East|Middle Eastern]] \n| 62,440\n| {{Percentage | 62440 | 2426235| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadians|Latin American]] \n| 34,805\n| {{Percentage | 34805 | 2426235| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Black Canadians|Black]] \n| 29,830 \n| {{Percentage | 29830 | 2426235| 1}}\n|-\n| Other \n| 41,780\n| {{Percentage | 41780| 2426235| 1}}\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; font-weight:bold\"\n|Total population \n| 2,426,235  \n| {{Percentage | 2426235 | 2426235 | 1}}\n|}\n{{Col-break|width=30%}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:20px;\"\n|+Top ethnic origins in Vancouver CMA (2016)<ref>{{cite web|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Vancouver [Census metropolitan area], British Columbia and British Columbia [Province]|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMACA&Code1=933&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1}}</ref>\n|-\n!Ethnic origin\n!Population\n!Percent\n|-\n|[[Overseas Chinese|Chinese]]\n|499,175\n|20.6%\n|-\n|[[English people|English]]\n|470,340\n|19.4%\n|-\n|[[Scottish people|Scottish]]\n|341,075\n|14.1%\n|-\n|[[Canadians|Canadian]]\n|331,205\n|13.7%\n|-\n|[[Irish people|Irish]]\n|275,355\n|11.3%\n|-\n|[[Indo-Canadian|Indian]]\n|243,135\n|10.1%\n|-\n|[[Ethnic German|German]]\n|222,025\n|9.2%\n|-\n|[[French people|French]]\n|147,835\n|6.1%\n|-\n|[[Filipinos|Filipino]]\n|133,925\n|5.5%\n|-\n|[[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]]\n|94,400\n|5.03%\n|-\n|}\n{{Col-break|width=33%}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n=== Aboriginal peoples ===\nAs of around 2009, 3% of residents of Vancouver state that they have at least some ancestry from the [[First Nations]], and of that 3%, over half state that they also have non-First Nations ancestry. A person with some First Nations ancestry may not necessarily identify as someone who is First Nations.<ref>Bloemraad, Irene. \"Diversity and Elected Officials in the City of Vancouver\" (Chapter 2). In: Andrew, Caroline, John Biles, Myer Siemiatycki, and Erin Tolley (editors). ''Electing a Diverse Canada: The Representation of Immigrants, Minorities, and Women''. [[UBC Press]], July 1, 2009. {{ISBN|0774858583}}, 9780774858588. Start p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EWCq1_Jg82gC&pg=PA46 46]. CITED: p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EWCq1_Jg82gC&pg=PA68 68].</ref>\n\nThere is a small community of [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|aboriginal]] people in Vancouver as well as in the surrounding metropolitan region, with the result that Vancouver constitutes the largest native community in the province, albeit an unincorporated one (i.e. not as a band government).{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}} There is an equally large or larger [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] contingent.\n\n=== British and other European origins ===\nMuch of the [[white people|white]] population consists of persons whose origins go back to [[Great Britain|Britain]] or [[Ireland]] and, until recently, British Columbians with British or Irish ancestry most likely came directly from those islands, rather than via [[Ontario]] or the [[Maritime Provinces]]. Until the 1960s, it was easier to purchase the ''[[The Times|Times]] ''of London and ''[[The Guardian]]'' in Vancouver than it was to find the ''[[The Globe and Mail|Toronto Globe and Mail]] ''or'' [[The Gazette (Montreal)|Montreal Gazette]]. ''\n\nOther large and historically important European ethnic groups consist of [[German people|Germans]], [[Dutch people|Dutch]], [[French people|French]] (of both European and Canadian origin), [[Ukrainians]], [[Scandinavia]]ns, [[Finns]], [[Italian people|Italian]]s, [[Croatian people|Croats]], [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], [[Greek people|Greeks]], and lately numerous [[Romanian people|Romanians]], [[Russian people|Russians]], [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]], [[Serbs]] and [[Polish people|Poles]].  Non-visible minorities such as newly arrived [[Eastern Europe]]ans and the new wave of [[Latin American]]s are also a feature of the city's ethnic landscape. Prior to the Hong Kong influx of the 1980s, the largest non-British Isles ethnic group in the city was [[German people|German]], followed by [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] and the [[Scandinavia]]n ethnicities. Most of these earlier East European immigrant  are fully assimilated or intermarried with other groups, although a new generation of [[East Europeans]] form a distinct linguistic and social community.\n\n=== Chinese origins ===\n{{main|Chinese Canadians in Greater Vancouver}}\nThe first Chinese immigrants to British Columbia were men who came to \"the British Colonies of [[Canada]],\" as they called British Columbia<!--ref Barkerville Chinese Museum; Gold Mountain is a ref to California only-->, for the [[Fraser Canyon Gold Rush]] of 1858 and a decade later to work on building the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]].\n\n=== South Asian origins ===\n{{main|South Asian Canadians in Greater Vancouver}}\nIndian immigrants first arrived in Vancouver during the late 19th century.<ref name=WRHp124>Walton-Roberts and Hiebert, ''[http://www.cjrs-rcsr.org/archives/20-1-2/WaltonRoberts-Hieberts.pdf Immigration, Entrepreneurship, and the Family] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018124820/http://www.cjrs-rcsr.org/archives/20-1-2/WaltonRoberts-Hieberts.pdf |date=2014-10-18 }}'', p. 124.</ref> Most ethnic South Asians in the Lower Mainland are Punjabi Sikhs. [[Surrey, BC|Surrey]] has the largest ethnic [[South Asian Canadians|South Asian]] population in Metro Vancouver, at 32.4%. The Newton neighbourhood in Surrey contains the highest percentage of ethnic Indians in a neighbourhood in Metro Vancouver.<ref name=\"makeup\">{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/Vancouver+maps+ethnic+makeup+Metro+Vancouver+interactive/5553001/story.html|title=The Vancouver Sun maps the ethnic makeup of Metro Vancouver (interactive)|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]|date=October 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Korean origins ===\t\n{{main|Korean Canadians}}\nAs of 2014 there are about 70,000 ethnic Koreans in the Vancouver area.<ref name=KoreanChrist>\"[http://blogs.vancouversun.com/2014/03/02/metros-70000-ethnic-koreans-most-drawn-to-enthusiastic-conservative-christianitys/ Metro\u2019s 70,000 ethnic Koreans: Most turn to fervent, conservative Christianity].\" ''[[Vancouver Sun]]''. March 2, 2014. Retrieved on December 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nAn [[H-Mart]] and several Korean restaurants are located on [[Robson Street]].<ref>Baker p. 162-163 (PDF 9-10/26).</ref> As of 2008 there are many Korean national students at the university and primary/secondary levels studying English.<ref name=Bakerp163>Baker p. 163 (PDF 10/26).</ref> Other areas with Korean businesses include [[Kingsway (Vancouver)|Kingsway]] in Vancouver, [[Burnaby, British Columbia|Burnaby]], and [[New Westminster, British Columbia|New Westminster]]; other areas in Vancouver; North Road in Burnaby and [[Coquitlam]], and areas of [[Port Coquitlam]].<ref name=AsianRelp5>Baker, Don and Larry DeVries. \"[http://www.ubcpress.ca/books/pdf/chapters/2010/AsianReligionsInBritishColimbia.pdf Introduction]\" ([https://web.archive.org/web/20160115105737/http://www.ubcpress.ca/books/pdf/chapters/2010/AsianReligionsInBritishColimbia.pdf Archive]). In: DeVries, Larry, Don Baker, and Dan Overmyer (editors). ''Asian Religions in British Columbia'' (Asian Religions and Society Series). [[University of British Columbia Press]], 2010. {{ISBN|978-0-7748-1662-5}}. p. 5.</ref> As of 2011 [[Coquitlam]] is a popular area of settlement for Koreans.<ref>\"[http://blogs.vancouversun.com/2011/10/20/ethnic-mapping-6-koreans-poles-scots-ukrainians-and-more/ Ethnic mapping 6: Koreans, Poles, Scots, Ukrainians and more].\" ''[[Vancouver Sun]]''. October 20, 2011. Retrieved on December 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nRimhak Ree (Yi Yimhak) came to Vancouver to study mathematics at the [[University of British Columbia]] in 1953, making him the first known ethnic Korean to live in the city.<ref>Baker p. 159 (PDF 6/26).</ref> There were about 50 ethnic Koreans in Vancouver in the mid-1960s. The first Korean United Church congregation in the city opened in 1965. Numbers of Korean immigration to Canada increased due to more permissive immigration laws established in the 1960s as well as the home country's political conflict and poverty. There were 1,670 ethnic Koreans in Vancouver by 1975, making up 16% of all ethnic Koreans in Canada and a 3000% increase from the mid-1960s population.<ref>Baker p. 160 (PDF 7/26).</ref> Korean immigration to Canada decreased after a more restrictive immigration law was enacted in 1978.<ref>Baker p. 160-161 (PDF 7-8/26).</ref>\n\nChristianity is a popular religion among ethnic Koreans. About 200 Korean churches are in the Vancouver area.<ref name=KoreanChrist/>\n\nIn 1986 Greater Vancouver had fewer than 5,000 ethnic Koreans. In 1991 the number had increased to 8,330. The number of ethnic Koreans in the Vancouver area increased by 69% in the period 1996 through 2001.<ref name=Bakerp162>Baker p. 162 (PDF 9/26).</ref> The number of university students from Korea choosing to study in Vancouver had become most of the Korean students studying in Canada by the late 1990s.<ref name=Bakerp163/> The first Korean grocery store in the North Road area opened in 2000.<ref name=AsianRelp5/> In 2001 28,850 ethnic Koreans live in Greater Vancouver, and this increased to 44,825 according to the 2006 census.<ref name=Bakerp162/>\n\n[[Canwest Global]] does a co-venture with the ''[[Canada Express]]'', a Korean publication, to serve ethnic Koreans. It previously published a Korean edition of the ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'' but later stopped. Daniel Ahadi and Catherine A. Murray, authors of \"Urban Mediascapes and Multicultural Flows: Assessing Vancouver\u2019s Communication Infrastructure,\" wrote that the Korean edition of the ''Vancouver Sun'' was \"error-fraught\".<ref>Ahadi, Daniel and Catherine A. Murray ([[Simon Fraser University]]). \"[http://pages.cmns.sfu.ca/daniel-ahadi/files/2010/07/Ahadi_Mediascapes.pdf Urban Mediascapes and Multicultural Flows: Assessing Vancouver\u2019s Communication Infrastructure]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6Vwfx1PjZ?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150129145839/http://pages.cmns.sfu.ca/daniel-ahadi/files/2010/07/Ahadi_Mediascapes.pdf Archive]). ''[[Canadian Journal of Communication]]'', Vol 34 (2009) p. 587-611. CITED: p. 596.</ref>\n\n===Other Asian ethnicities===\nOther significant Asian ethnic groups in Vancouver are [[Vietnamese Canadian|Vietnamese]], [[Filipino Canadian|Filipino]], [[Cambodian Canadian|Cambodian]] and [[Japanese Canadian|Japanese]]. In Vancouver the term 'Asian' is normally used to refer only to [[East Asian]] and [[Southeast Asian]] peoples, while [[South Asian Canadians in Greater Vancouver|South Asians]] are usually referred to as [[Indo-Canadian]] or East Indians. Technically, though, the term 'Asian' may refer to either group, and also to the large [[Persian people|Persian]] and other [[Middle Eastern]] populations as well as elements from [[Central Asia]].\n\n===Tables of ethnicities (Vancouver CMA)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\"\n|- \"\n!Ethnic origin\n!Population (2016)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMACA&Code1=933&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Ethnic%20origin&TABID=1#fnb118-ref|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Vancouver [Census metropolitan area], British Columbia and British Columbia [Province] Ethnic Origin|publisher